    \"timestamp\": \"2026-03-12T19:02:22.347Z\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"subject\": \"Structuring Resume Commands\",\n          \"description\": \"I'm synthesizing the resume commands into a concise, actionable guide. The flags are straightforward, `--resume` and `-r`. Additionally, I'm noting the index/UUID and `/resume` browser options, and `/chat resume <name>` commands for saved sessions. I aim to create a neat, user-friendly response.\",\n          \"timestamp\": \"2026-03-12T19:02:25.373Z\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"tokens\": {\n        \"input\": 5421,\n        \"output\": 471,\n        \"cached\": 3712,\n        \"thoughts\": 176,\n        \"tool\": 0,\n        \"total\": 6068\n      },\n      \"model\": \"gemini-3-flash-preview\",\n      \"toolCalls\": [\n        {\n          \"id\": \"cli_help_1773342113832_0\",\n          \"name\": \"cli_help\",\n          \"args\": {\n            \"question\": \"how to resume a session after quitting\"\n          },\n          \"result\": [\n            {\n              \"functionResponse\": {\n                \"id\": \"cli_help_1773342113832_0\",\n                \"name\": \"cli_help\",\n                \"response\": {\n                  \"output\": \"Subagent 'cli_help' finished.\\nTermination Reason: GOAL\\nResult:\\n{\\n  \\\"answer\\\": \\\"To resume a session in Gemini CLI after quitting, you can use the following methods:\\\\n\\\\n### From the Command Line\\\\nWhen starting the CLI, use the `--resume` (or `-r`) flag:\\\\n\\\\n*   **Resume the latest session:**\\\\n    ```bash\\\\n    gemini --resume\\\\n    ```\\\\n    This immediately loads the most recent conversation for the current project.\\\\n\\\\n*   **List available sessions:**\\\\n    If you want to resume a specific older session, first list them to find the index or ID:\\\\n    ```bash\\\\n    gemini --list-sessions\\\\n    ```\\\\n\\\\n*   **Resume by index or ID:**\\\\n    Use the index number from the list or the full session UUID:\\\\n    ```bash\\\\n    gemini --resume 1\\\\n    # OR\\\\n    gemini --resume a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890\\\\n    ```\\\\n\\\\n### From Within the Interactive Interface\\\\nIf you have already started a new session and want to switch to a previous one:\\\\n\\\\n*   **Session Browser:** Type the `/resume` slash command to open an interactive, searchable browser of your past sessions.\\\\n    ```text\\\\n    /resume\\\\n    ```\\\\n    Use the arrow keys to browse, `/` to search, and **Enter** to select and load a session.\\\\n\\\\n*   **Resume a Named Session:** If you previously saved a session using `/chat save <name>`, you can resume it using:\\\\n    ```text\\\\n    /chat resume <name>\\\\n    ```\\\\n\\\\n### Key Details\\\\n*   **Automatic Saving:** Gemini CLI automatically records your conversation history, tool executions, and token usage.\\\\n*   **Project Specificity:** Sessions are tied to your project's root directory. Switching directories will switch the available session history.\\\\n*   **Storage Location:** Sessions are stored locally in `~/.gemini/tmp/<project_hash>/chats/`.\\\\n*   **Retention:** By default, sessions are retained for 30 days, though this can be configured in your `settings.json`.\\\",\\n  \\\"sources\\\": [\\n    \\\"cli/session-management.md\\\",\\n    \\\"cli/tutorials/session-management.md\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\"\n                }\n              }\n            }\n          ],\n          \"status\": \"success\",\n          \"timestamp\": \"2026-03-12T19:02:25.467Z\",\n          \"resultDisplay\": \"\\nSubagent cli_help Finished\\n\\nTermination Reason:\\n GOAL\\n\\nResult:\\n{\\n  \\\"answer\\\": \\\"To resume a session in Gemini CLI after quitting, you can use the following methods:\\\\n\\\\n### From the Command Line\\\\nWhen starting the CLI, use the `--resume` (or `-r`) flag:\\\\n\\\\n*   **Resume the latest session:**\\\\n    ```bash\\\\n    gemini --resume\\\\n    ```\\\\n    This immediately loads the most recent conversation for the current project.\\\\n\\\\n*   **List available sessions:**\\\\n    If you want to resume a specific older session, first list them to find the index or ID:\\\\n    ```bash\\\\n    gemini --list-sessions\\\\n    ```\\\\n\\\\n*   **Resume by index or ID:**\\\\n    Use the index number from the list or the full session UUID:\\\\n    ```bash\\\\n    gemini --resume 1\\\\n    # OR\\\\n    gemini --resume a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890\\\\n    ```\\\\n\\\\n### From Within the Interactive Interface\\\\nIf you have already started a new session and want to switch to a previous one:\\\\n\\\\n*   **Session Browser:** Type the `/resume` slash command to open an interactive, searchable browser of your past sessions.\\\\n    ```text\\\\n    /resume\\\\n    ```\\\\n    Use the arrow keys to browse, `/` to search, and **Enter** to select and load a session.\\\\n\\\\n*   **Resume a Named Session:** If you previously saved a session using `/chat save <name>`, you can resume it using:\\\\n    ```text\\\\n    /chat resume <name>\\\\n    ```\\\\n\\\\n### Key Details\\\\n*   **Automatic Saving:** Gemini CLI automatically records your conversation history, tool executions, and token usage.\\\\n*   **Project Specificity:** Sessions are tied to your project's root directory. Switching directories will switch the available session history.\\\\n*   **Storage Location:** Sessions are stored locally in `~/.gemini/tmp/<project_hash>/chats/`.\\\\n*   **Retention:** By default, sessions are retained for 30 days, though this can be configured in your `settings.json`.\\\",\\n  \\\"sources\\\": [\\n    \\\"cli/session-management.md\\\",\\n    \\\"cli/tutorials/session-management.md\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\\n\",\n          \"displayName\": \"CLI Help Agent\",\n          \"description\": \"Specialized in answering questions about how users use you, (Gemini CLI): features, documentation, and current runtime configuration.\",\n          \"renderOutputAsMarkdown\": true\n        }\n      ]\n    },